850
00:55:34,314 --> 00:55:35,974
The summer breeze
blows the sweet...

851
00:55:36,074 --> 00:55:38,018
perfume from our garden
into my kitchen...

852
00:55:38,118 --> 00:55:39,719
...and I think of you.

853
00:55:39,819 --> 00:55:42,947
How you love flowers.

854
00:55:43,223 --> 00:55:45,733
I'm sorry I can't visit you now.

855
00:55:45,833 --> 00:55:48,873
But you should know
I always love you.

856
00:55:49,129 --> 00:55:51,129
Dear Honey Bee:

857
00:55:52,132 --> 00:55:54,768
Sometimes I want to
help your mom...

858
00:55:54,868 --> 00:55:58,788
...but she thinks it is best
if I leave her alone.

859
00:55:59,272 --> 00:56:04,232
I hope that she will get well
and let us visit again real soon.

860
00:56:05,345 --> 00:56:07,939
Love always, Grandma.

861
00:56:22,962 --> 00:56:26,066
BRIDGET: Dear Nasrin,
you deserve more than a letter...

862
00:56:26,166 --> 00:56:30,262
...but as you probably guessed,
I suck at goodbyes.

863
00:56:31,571 --> 00:56:35,208
You said archaeology
is more than finding bones.

864
00:56:35,308 --> 00:56:37,143
And you were right.

865
00:56:37,243 --> 00:56:41,348
People do have a power over us,
even after they're gone.

866
00:56:41,448 --> 00:56:45,685
When my mother took her own life,
I tried to forget the past.

867
00:56:45,785 --> 00:56:51,223
I ran away from the pain because...
Well, I guess I was afraid.

868
00:56:52,092 --> 00:56:56,893
But the past is always with us,
and it's time I stop running.

869
00:56:57,063 --> 00:57:00,191
Thank you for the lesson. Bridget.

870
00:57:11,277 --> 00:57:15,015
Alas, Florizel, I know not
'tween the turkey club sandwich...

871
00:57:15,115 --> 00:57:17,018
...or the Hamlet
and cheese omelet.

872
00:57:17,118 --> 00:57:18,118
What say you?

873
00:57:18,218 --> 00:57:20,453
Well, I come not to bury Caesar,
but to have a caesar salad.

874
00:57:20,553 --> 00:57:23,283
Ooh.
- Now tell me about you.

875
00:57:23,456 --> 00:57:25,325
Only child? Brothers and sisters?

876
00:57:25,425 --> 00:57:26,993
Only child.

877
00:57:27,093 --> 00:57:30,764
Oh, no. Well, not for long.
My mom is gonna have a baby.

878
00:57:30,864 --> 00:57:34,100
It's kind of a long story.
Or not that long of a story.

879
00:57:34,200 --> 00:57:37,692
Hey. Am I interrupting?
- No, not at all.

880
00:57:37,871 --> 00:57:39,340
Great. Can we take
this chair? Thanks.

881
00:57:39,440 --> 00:57:40,440
Sure.

882
00:57:40,540 --> 00:57:42,540
Sit down.

883
00:57:42,609 --> 00:57:44,144
Do you know Julia? Lan.

884
00:57:44,244 --> 00:57:46,379
Yeah, we've met once or twice.

885
00:57:46,479 --> 00:57:48,748
Lan's family are in the theater,
just like mine.

886
00:57:48,848 --> 00:57:50,851
You went to RADA with
20 of my friends.

887
00:57:50,951 --> 00:57:51,951
RADA?

888
00:57:52,051 --> 00:57:54,721
Royal Academy of Dramatic Art,
it's in London.

889
00:57:54,821 --> 00:57:56,056
Oh.

890
00:57:56,156 --> 00:57:57,892
Did you hear about
Patrick O'Houlihan?

891
00:57:57,992 --> 00:57:58,992
Lucky bastard.

892
00:57:59,092 --> 00:58:01,161
I'm hoping to catch the show
when I go to New York.

893
00:58:01,261 --> 00:58:04,531
We should get a whole group of
people together and surprise him.

894
00:58:04,631 --> 00:58:06,631
Sounds fun.

895
00:58:08,134 --> 00:58:10,898
Jam, on your lip.
- Oh.

896
00:58:11,804 --> 00:58:13,862
You know, we really should order.

897
00:58:13,962 --> 00:58:16,276
We've got a rehearsal
to get back to.

898
00:58:16,376 --> 00:58:18,376
Caesar salad, please.

899
00:58:19,245 --> 00:58:22,765
[JAMES OTTO'S 'SUNSET MAN'
PLAYING ON STEREO]

900
00:58:23,583 --> 00:58:25,318
BRIDGET: Hello?

901
00:58:25,418 --> 00:58:27,418
Excuse me, sir?

902
00:58:30,423 --> 00:58:32,721
Hi. Greta?

903
00:58:33,760 --> 00:58:36,194
Um, I'm really sorry.

904
00:58:36,362 --> 00:58:39,593
I should have called first, but I'm...

905
00:58:39,766 --> 00:58:42,646
I think I know my
own granddaughter.

906
00:58:45,071 --> 00:58:47,331
You're not running
away from home,

907
00:58:47,431 --> 00:58:49,431
are you?

908
00:58:50,410 --> 00:58:54,005
No, actually, I'm coming home,
from Turkey.

909
00:58:54,714 --> 00:58:57,994
That's an interesting
sense of direction.

910
00:59:04,524 --> 00:59:06,754
So you fix your own car?

911
00:59:07,327 --> 00:59:12,230
Cars are easy.
It's people you need a manual for.

912
00:59:20,473 --> 00:59:23,499
Come on in. You
must be exhausted.

913
00:59:23,676 --> 00:59:25,745
BRIDGET:
Yep. You don't even know.

914
00:59:25,845 --> 00:59:29,845
GRETA: Why don't you go right up
and get some rest?

915
00:59:31,451 --> 00:59:33,451
Hello.
- Hey.

916
00:59:33,553 --> 00:59:35,553
Hey. Wow, you look great.

917
00:59:36,055 --> 00:59:37,790
You think? Thanks.

918
00:59:37,890 --> 00:59:39,292
So, what's the occasion?

919
00:59:39,392 --> 00:59:41,758
Um, lan asked me to dinner.

920
00:59:42,895 --> 00:59:45,131
I mean, I can be so
dense sometimes.

921
00:59:45,231 --> 00:59:48,368
I didn't even know
that he liked me that way.

922
00:59:48,468 --> 00:59:50,698
Did you?
- No.

923
00:59:51,437 --> 00:59:54,440
But, then again,
I can be pretty dense too so...

924
00:59:54,540 --> 00:59:55,400
I just thought he...

925
00:59:55,500 --> 00:59:57,043
might have said
something to you...

926
00:59:57,143 --> 01:00:00,246
...because you guys have become
such good friends. You know men.

927
01:00:00,346 --> 01:00:03,249
So you're going, then?
You're going on a date?

928
01:00:03,349 --> 01:00:07,487
Yeah. I mean, he's gorgeous,
and he's really nice, and...

929
01:00:07,587 --> 01:00:10,954
...he's really real.
For an actor, anyway.

930
01:00:11,958 --> 01:00:15,128
I just thought, why
not give it a chance?

931
01:00:15,228 --> 01:00:17,818
We have so much
in common anyway,

932
01:00:17,918 --> 01:00:19,918
and it might really work.

933
01:00:20,400 --> 01:00:22,936
I know you need sleep
before rehearsal tomorrow.

934
01:00:23,036 --> 01:00:26,026
I'll be really quiet
when I come home,

935
01:00:26,126 --> 01:00:28,126
but don't wait up.

936
01:00:28,841 --> 01:00:32,868
I won't.
- Okay. Well, have a good night.

937
01:00:47,660 --> 01:00:49,329
Thanks, Greta.

938
01:00:49,429 --> 01:00:51,698
Grandma.
I'm sorry, I don't know which...

939
01:00:51,798 --> 01:00:54,198
I haven't heard from you in...

940
01:00:56,169 --> 01:00:57,470
...10 or 12 years.

941
01:00:57,570 --> 01:00:59,005
I know.

942
01:00:59,105 --> 01:01:02,385
Look, my dad,
he hid your letters from me.

943
01:01:03,843 --> 01:01:06,334
I just found them this summer.

944
01:01:07,347 --> 01:01:09,347
I see.

945
01:01:11,150 --> 01:01:13,150
So I guess we can skip...

946
01:01:14,253 --> 01:01:16,733
...junior high and high school.

947
01:01:19,592 --> 01:01:21,592
How's college?

948
01:01:22,929 --> 01:01:26,165
It's good. I haven't declared
a major yet, but...

949
01:01:26,265 --> 01:01:28,265
Got a fella?

950
01:01:29,202 --> 01:01:31,202
No, not at the moment.

951
01:01:31,471 --> 01:01:35,008
Listen, you ought to kick up
some trouble now...

952
01:01:35,108 --> 01:01:39,841
...because in 40 years,
they'll all tell you you're old.

953
01:02:12,845 --> 01:02:15,805
You made that the
summer you visited.

954
01:02:15,915 --> 01:02:19,195
You must have been about
6 or 7 years old.

955
01:02:19,218 --> 01:02:21,218
I've been here before?

956
01:02:22,989 --> 01:02:25,469
Well, that was a long time ago.

957
01:02:37,437 --> 01:02:39,667
TIBBY: 'Return to sender.'

958
01:02:40,807 --> 01:02:42,807
Super.

959
01:02:46,379 --> 01:02:48,923
O, the fates. How
would he look to see...

960
01:02:49,023 --> 01:02:51,250
his work, so noble,
vilely bound up?

961
01:02:51,350 --> 01:02:53,219
KERR: Stop.

962
01:02:53,319 --> 01:02:55,054
Again.

963
01:02:55,154 --> 01:02:58,891
O, the fates. How would he look to
see his work, so noble...

964
01:02:58,991 --> 01:03:00,991
KERR: Stop. Again.

965
01:03:01,060 --> 01:03:03,329
O, the fates.
How would he look to see his...

966
01:03:03,429 --> 01:03:06,265
Stop right there.
Carmen, is there a problem?

967
01:03:06,365 --> 01:03:09,035
No. I don't know.
Did I say the wrong line?

968
01:03:09,135 --> 01:03:10,536
No.

969
01:03:10,636 --> 01:03:13,539
You're supposed to sound like
a woman in love.

970
01:03:13,639 --> 01:03:18,039
You sound like a woman
who's about to have a root canal.

971
01:03:21,147 --> 01:03:23,147
Again.

972
01:03:24,650 --> 01:03:27,120
O, the fates. How
would he look to s...

973
01:03:27,220 --> 01:03:29,245
I hear the drill.

974
01:03:32,592 --> 01:03:34,592
Again.

975
01:03:38,130 --> 01:03:40,130
Carmen, wait.

976
01:03:41,434 --> 01:03:44,404
I'm sorry. I don't mean to be
screwing everything up like this.

977
01:03:44,504 --> 01:03:48,904
You've got great instincts.
You just need to trust them.

978
01:03:49,442 --> 01:03:52,512
Why don't we work on it together,
tonight?

979
01:03:52,612 --> 01:03:53,682
No. It's okay.

980
01:03:53,782 --> 01:03:56,902
I should just work
on it alone. Thanks.

981
01:04:27,947 --> 01:04:30,780
Oh, my God, that was torture.
- Hey.

982
01:04:31,450 --> 01:04:33,523
All I could think
about was drawing you.

983
01:04:33,623 --> 01:04:35,855
Sorry to interfere with
your concentration.

984
01:04:35,955 --> 01:04:38,423
That's okay. I don't mind.

985
01:04:42,628 --> 01:04:43,896
Okay.

986
01:04:43,996 --> 01:04:45,198
Okay.

987
01:04:45,298 --> 01:04:47,700
Well, I guess you have to get back
to class, huh?

988
01:04:47,800 --> 01:04:49,800
Yes.

989
01:04:50,469 --> 01:04:52,469
I guess.

990
01:04:54,040 --> 01:04:55,575
I'll see you later.

991
01:04:55,675 --> 01:04:57,675
I'll see you.

992
01:05:07,353 --> 01:05:09,353
KOSTOS: Lena.

993
01:05:19,599 --> 01:05:23,592
There was no choice
but to be married.

994
01:05:23,769 --> 01:05:26,274
My grandfather, I
think he could see

995
01:05:26,374 --> 01:05:27,673
I did not love her.

996
01:05:27,773 --> 01:05:32,369
And then that day at the funeral,
she saw it too.

997
01:05:32,945 --> 01:05:35,609
That my heart would
always belong...

998
01:05:35,709 --> 01:05:36,883
to someone else.

999
01:05:36,983 --> 01:05:39,611
And that is when she told me...

1000
01:05:40,753 --> 01:05:42,846
...there never was a baby.

1001
01:05:44,957 --> 01:05:47,277
We had the marriage annulled.

1002
01:05:48,561 --> 01:05:51,359
I wanted to tell you right away.

1003
01:05:54,333 --> 01:05:56,843
But I was afraid. I didn't think

1004
01:05:56,943 --> 01:06:00,143
I had the right to
ask your forgiveness.

1005
01:06:00,272 --> 01:06:03,492
Maybe it's too much
to hope you could...

1006
01:06:03,592 --> 01:06:04,944
Forgive you?

1007
01:06:05,044 --> 01:06:07,044
I forgive you.

1008
01:06:08,814 --> 01:06:09,814
Lena, I thought...

1009
01:06:09,914 --> 01:06:12,151
That I'd be waiting
for you to come here?

1010
01:06:12,251 --> 01:06:15,311
No. I didn't expect anything.

1011
01:06:15,488 --> 01:06:18,368
I just wanted you
to know the truth.

1012
01:06:19,492 --> 01:06:21,492
Well...

1013
01:06:21,661 --> 01:06:23,661
...thank you.

1014
01:06:26,065 --> 01:06:29,905
The truth is we loved each other
a long time ago.

1015
01:06:32,171 --> 01:06:34,473
And my life is so different now.

1016
01:06:34,573 --> 01:06:37,041
Lena, I'm sorry.

1017
01:06:38,444 --> 01:06:39,812
I'm so sorry.

1018
01:06:39,912 --> 01:06:41,514
No, it's okay. It's fine.

1019
